00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:22.160
ANDREW LO: OK.

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:25.280
What I'd like to do today is
to continue where we left off

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.510
last time in talking about this
risk-reward trade-off, which

00:00:29.510 --> 00:00:33.170
ultimately will allow us
to be able to figure out

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:37.310
how to calculate the proper
discount rate for any project

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:38.480
under the sun.

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:43.220
Now, where we left off last time
was this equation and the one

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:44.240
after it.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.910
This equation we
actually derived.

00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:48.950
I showed you how to
get this equation

00:00:48.950 --> 00:00:54.140
from this particular bullet
and the tangency line.

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:56.690
And today I am going to
give you names for them.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:01:00.680
The bullet, as we've said
before, is the frontier.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:02.450
It's the set of
frontier portfolios.

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:04.910
And the upper arc
of that bullet is

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:06.740
called the efficient frontier.

00:01:06.740 --> 00:01:09.590
Now the tangency line
has a special name too.

00:01:09.590 --> 00:01:15.140
That tangency line is known
as the capital market line

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:19.220
because it represents what
all efficient capital markets

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:22.160
should represent in terms
of risk-reward trade-off.

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:25.100
So if you are an efficient
portfolio manager,

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:27.190
you want to be on that line.

00:01:27.190 --> 00:01:28.650
OK?

00:01:28.650 --> 00:01:32.340
So the capital market
line, the equation

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:36.020
for that tangency
line, is given by this.

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:39.030
The expected rate of return
is equal to the risk-free rate

00:01:39.030 --> 00:01:42.090
plus some kind of risk
premium, where the risk premium

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:46.800
is given by a multiple of
the market's risk premium,

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.310
or the market excess return.

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:53.250
And the multiple
is simply the ratio

00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:57.420
of the riskiness of
your efficient portfolio

00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:59.880
relative to the
market portfolio,

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:02.940
or the tangency portfolio.

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:04.650
If it's twice as
risky, you're going

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:06.040
to get twice the risk premium.

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:07.680
If it's half as
risky, you're going

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:09.639
to get half the risk premium.

00:02:09.639 --> 00:02:11.460
And we said last
time that, while this

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:16.110
is helpful and interesting
and even possibly useful,

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:17.970
it's going to be of
limited applicability

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:22.020
because not everything is
an efficient portfolio.

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:24.480
What we mean by an
efficient portfolio,

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:28.410
the intuition for what an
efficient portfolio is,

00:02:28.410 --> 00:02:33.470
is a portfolio where
you cannot do better.

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:37.580
By cannot do better, I mean you
can't get less risk for that

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:43.070
same level of return, or you
can't get more expected return

00:02:43.070 --> 00:02:44.990
for that same level of risk.

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:47.550
That's what we mean by
an efficient portfolio.

00:02:47.550 --> 00:02:50.030
It's the best you can do.

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:54.440
Now, most investments are,
frankly, not efficient.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.040
If you pick an arbitrary
stock, like IBM, that's

00:02:58.040 --> 00:02:59.510
not an efficient portfolio.

00:02:59.510 --> 00:03:01.100
It doesn't mean it's no good.

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:02.970
It doesn't mean you
don't want to hold it.

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:04.820
But it means that
you would never

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:11.900
want to hold just IBM because if
you mixed IBM with other stuff,

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:13.820
you can always do better.

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:16.070
By do better, again
I'm going to reiterate,

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:19.160
I mean you can have
higher expected return

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:23.630
for the same level of risk or
lower risk for the same level

00:03:23.630 --> 00:03:24.540
of expected return.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:25.970
That's what I mean by do better.

00:03:25.970 --> 00:03:29.450
So you would never want
to hold IBM just by itself

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:30.890
because you can
do better, right?

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:35.780
You can do better in getting
up to that Northwest quadrant

00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:39.150
from the IBM point.

00:03:39.150 --> 00:03:43.130
But even though IBM
is not efficient,

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:45.200
you might still want to hold it.

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.910
And more importantly,
you might still

00:03:46.910 --> 00:03:49.760
want to know what the
appropriate discount

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:56.090
rate is for companies
that are like IBM.

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:57.800
That's what we're
going to do next.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:02.660
Where I left off last time was
not the capital market line,

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:07.130
but this equation, which I did
not derive, but which I argued

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:10.640
comes from the
equilibrium argument

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:14.990
that Bill Sharpe
made 50 years ago.

00:04:14.990 --> 00:04:18.440
And this really
relies on the fact

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.079
that, if markets
are in equilibrium,

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:23.660
there is a relationship
between risk

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:27.980
and expected return for
all securities, not just

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:29.900
efficient portfolios.

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:34.610
But any arbitrary security
has to satisfy this equation

00:04:34.610 --> 00:04:38.090
if supply equals demand,
if there's an equilibrium.

00:04:38.090 --> 00:04:40.580
If everybody holds the
tangency portfolio,

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:42.590
and the tangency
portfolio therefore

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:45.860
is the market portfolio,
in that situation,

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:47.660
this equation has to hold.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:51.120
So where we left off was to
try to interpret this equation.

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:53.510
This equation is almost
identical to the capital market

00:04:53.510 --> 00:04:54.034
line.

00:04:54.034 --> 00:04:55.200
There's only one difference.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:58.910
The only difference is that
the multiplier, the thing that

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:01.520
multiplies the
market risk premium,

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:03.785
is not sigma p over sigma m.

00:05:03.785 --> 00:05:05.420
It is beta.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:09.620
And beta, we said, was the
ratio of the covariance

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:11.550
of an asset with
the market divided

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:12.800
by the variance of the market.

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:17.920
It is a measure of that
particular asset's riskiness.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:20.720
It's not variance anymore,
or standard deviation,

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:21.990
it's something else.

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:24.140
And so I want to spend
this class talking

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:28.880
about what that something else
is and why it makes sense.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.910
First of all, let's make sure
we understand the equation.

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:33.920
I want to do a
few special cases,

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:37.070
and then I'm going to take
apart this notion of beta

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:41.400
as being the right measure
of risk in all circumstances.

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:45.480
So the first thing I want to
do is to look at some examples.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.262
Let's take an example where
the beta is equal to 1.

00:05:48.262 --> 00:05:51.260
If the beta is equal to
1, what that's saying

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:57.320
is that the covariance between
the asset and the market

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.570
divided by the
variance of the market,

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:01.970
that number is equal to 1.

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:04.460
If that's the case,
then it turns out

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:08.660
that the expected rate of return
of this asset with a beta of 1

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:11.457
is going to be just equal
to the market risk premium.

00:06:11.457 --> 00:06:13.790
Or the expected return is
equal to the market's expected

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:15.410
rate of return.

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:17.807
When beta is equal to
1, the Rf's cancel out,

00:06:17.807 --> 00:06:19.640
and the expected rate
of return of the asset

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:23.570
is equal to the expected
rate of return on the market.

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:25.520
Now, what about if the
beta is equal to 0?

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:29.590
If the beta is equal to 0, then
you get the risk-free rate.

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:33.010
It's important to realize
that if the beta of an asset

00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:35.620
is equal to 0, it doesn't
mean that the asset has

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:38.670
no volatility.

00:06:38.670 --> 00:06:41.490
In the past, when
we've looked at mixing

00:06:41.490 --> 00:06:45.360
the risk-free asset,
T-bills, with the market,

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:48.990
we know that when the
risk-free asset is included,

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:51.130
you get that straight line.

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:54.150
And it's because the risk-free
asset has no covariance.

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:56.200
It has no risk at all.

00:06:56.200 --> 00:07:01.050
But now, with an asset
that has a beta of 0,

00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:02.850
you're getting the
risk-free return,

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:06.990
even though an asset
with a beta of 0

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:09.430
still may have some volatility.

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:11.040
It's not the risk-free asset.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:12.960
It's any asset with a 0 beta.

00:07:16.310 --> 00:07:18.290
The third observation
that I want to make

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:21.230
is when a beta is negative.

00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:24.770
With the beta that's negative,
the expected rate of return

00:07:24.770 --> 00:07:28.350
is actually less than
the risk-free rate.

00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:30.260
Now that's really odd.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:33.130
I've got an asset that is risky.

00:07:33.130 --> 00:07:37.810
But just because it
has a negative beta,

00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:41.360
the expected rate of return is
less than the risk-free rate.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:45.740
That means that you are willing
to take a lower expected rate

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:48.920
of return than the risk-free
rate for an asset that

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.757
has this weird property
of negative beta.

00:07:52.757 --> 00:07:55.090
And the question I want to
answer today is, why is that?

00:07:55.090 --> 00:07:58.240
Why is it the case
that you might

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:01.540
be willing to take such
a low rate of return?

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:04.420
And actually, if the
beta is negative enough,

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:06.280
if this beta is
negative enough, it

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:10.560
could be the case that the
expected rate of return

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:13.060
is negative.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:16.920
In other words, you might
be willing to pay somebody

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:21.300
for the privilege of
bearing that risk.

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:23.190
That seems completely
counterintuitive.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:26.760
Why would you be willing
to pay to take risk?

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:29.610
You should be getting
paid to take risk, right?

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:33.690
That's the standard
hypothesis that we

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:36.700
come into the
financial markets with.

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:38.695
So yeah, Leah?

00:08:38.695 --> 00:08:40.514
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:40.514 --> 00:08:41.514
ANDREW LO: That's right.

00:08:41.514 --> 00:08:43.789
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:43.789 --> 00:08:44.810
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:49.070
That's exactly the intuition
for all three of these cases.

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:53.240
It turns out that the
beta, remember, has

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:56.400
this covariance term in there.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:59.900
And it is going to
turn out that, if you

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:04.910
can find an asset that
is negatively correlated

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:09.050
to the tangency portfolio,
that is going to be

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:11.080
of tremendous value to you.

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:13.580
It's very, very valuable.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:14.310
Now, OK.

00:09:14.310 --> 00:09:16.280
Let me try to explain
the logic behind it.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.420
And we're going to
do a few examples.

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:23.270
So let's go through the basic
logic of what's going on.

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:26.810
The tangency portfolio
plays a central role

00:09:26.810 --> 00:09:28.760
in that everybody
in the world is

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:31.280
going to want to have
a portfolio that's

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:33.020
a combination of
the risk-free asset

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:35.360
and the tangency portfolio.

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:37.490
That's fact number one.

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:44.720
Fact number two, the tangency
portfolio is a portfolio that

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:50.300
has the aggregate measure
of the total amount of risk

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:55.140
in the economy that cannot be
diversified beyond that point.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:59.360
In other words, in
order to get lower risk

00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:01.730
than this particular
portfolio, you

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:06.540
have to decrease your
expected rate of return.

00:10:06.540 --> 00:10:10.040
There's no way to get lower
risk and keep that same level

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:10.940
of expected return.

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:11.856
You can't go this way.

00:10:11.856 --> 00:10:13.660
You have to go down this line.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:14.480
OK?

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:19.610
So if you're going to
hold a portfolio of purely

00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:22.970
risky securities,
then basically this

00:10:22.970 --> 00:10:25.220
is the best that you can do.

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:27.380
This is the best
trade-off that you can

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:31.140
get in terms of risk-reward.

00:10:31.140 --> 00:10:35.210
So right away you know
that this market portfolio

00:10:35.210 --> 00:10:37.850
plays a very special role.

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:44.630
It is really the representation
of the aggregate risk

00:10:44.630 --> 00:10:46.680
in the stock market.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:50.600
And that's why it can serve as
a kind of a benchmark for what

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:52.042
the stock market is doing.

00:10:52.042 --> 00:10:54.000
We're going to come back
to that benchmark idea

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:55.590
in a few minutes.

00:10:55.590 --> 00:11:00.890
So, if you have a security
that is very highly

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:03.740
correlated to that
market return,

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:05.660
then that's not going
to help you in terms

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.690
of your own diversification.

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:11.930
If, on the other hand, you have
a security that is negatively

00:11:11.930 --> 00:11:14.510
correlated with that
market portfolio,

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:17.290
that's going to help you a lot.

00:11:17.290 --> 00:11:20.080
And if it's going
to help you a lot,

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:21.929
you're willing to pay for it.

00:11:21.929 --> 00:11:24.220
When you're willing to pay
for it, what does that mean?

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:27.370
You drive the price today high.

00:11:27.370 --> 00:11:30.230
And therefore, the
expected rate of return,

00:11:30.230 --> 00:11:34.360
which is the return between
today and next period, that

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:37.690
becomes lower.

00:11:37.690 --> 00:11:41.470
So an asset that
helps you hedge what

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:45.550
is essentially unhedgedgeable,
in other words, the market

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:49.504
portfolio, that can
benefit you a great deal.

00:11:49.504 --> 00:11:50.920
As a result, it's
going to be very

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:56.740
hard to find negative
beta securities or assets.

00:11:56.740 --> 00:11:59.470
But in any case, this
relationship really

00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:04.240
tells you that, given a
particular covariance,

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:07.210
you can measure the
expected rate of return

00:12:07.210 --> 00:12:09.250
that you ought to be getting.

00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:11.200
And this relationship
is so important

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:12.590
that we give it a separate name.

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:16.780
It's called the security market
line, not the capital market

00:12:16.780 --> 00:12:19.000
line, but the
security market line

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.290
because this applies to
every single security

00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:24.960
in your entire universe.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:25.960
Yeah, Dennis?

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:27.210
AUDIENCE: You say it's
hard to find something

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:28.085
with a negative beta.

00:12:28.085 --> 00:12:30.082
But when you short
something, does

00:12:30.082 --> 00:12:31.790
that mean you're
getting a negative beta?

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.090
ANDREW LO: It is.

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:34.120
You do.

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:36.250
But the problem with
shorting something

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:38.410
where you get a
negative beta, you also

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:42.470
get a negative expected
rate of return typically.

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:44.560
So what you want to
have is an asset that's

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:46.630
got a positive beta--
or negative beta,

00:12:46.630 --> 00:12:48.550
but a positive expected
rate of return.

00:12:48.550 --> 00:12:50.500
That's what's very rare.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:52.870
But you can manufacture a
negative beta security very

00:12:52.870 --> 00:12:55.480
easily by just shorting it.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:57.460
The problem is that
when you short a stock,

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.710
you're going to also get a
very negative expected rate

00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:00.364
of return.

00:13:00.364 --> 00:13:01.780
And that doesn't
help you in terms

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:05.190
of producing an attractive
investment opportunity.

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:07.660
Ken, question?

00:13:07.660 --> 00:13:12.160
AUDIENCE: So, what's an example
of a negative beta security?

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:15.550
ANDREW LO: Well, it's
very hard to come by.

00:13:15.550 --> 00:13:19.540
But the closest thing that
exists in markets today

00:13:19.540 --> 00:13:26.770
is stocks that are involved in
gold production, gold mining

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:27.970
stocks.

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:31.620
That has a beta of around 0,
but sometimes it's negative.

00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:32.620
Sometimes it's positive.

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:34.150
But it's small.

00:13:34.150 --> 00:13:37.510
So that's an example, but
that's about the only example

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:40.330
that we can come up
with in the data that

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:42.520
looks slightly negative.

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:47.920
By and large, most of the betas
in the data sets are positive.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:51.130
And they're actually
clustered around 1.

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:57.521
So the typical beta is in the
neighborhood of 0.5 to 1.5.

00:13:57.521 --> 00:13:58.020
All right.

00:13:58.020 --> 00:13:59.350
Now, before we start
looking at the data--

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:01.225
I'm going to show you
some data in a minute--

00:14:01.225 --> 00:14:05.930
I want to take the security
market line and apply it.

00:14:05.930 --> 00:14:08.130
So the security market
line I did not derive.

00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:09.550
I want to make that clear.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:11.966
And for those of you who are
interested in the derivation,

00:14:11.966 --> 00:14:14.200
you can take a look at the
appendix in the Brealey,

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:14.950
Meyers, and Allen.

00:14:14.950 --> 00:14:16.720
They provide the derivation.

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:19.600
It's a little bit messy,
but with a little bit

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:23.230
of matrix algebra you
can work through it.

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:26.720
But the implications
are extremely important,

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:29.390
so I want all of you
to know how to use it.

00:14:29.390 --> 00:14:32.050
So it may look pretty
simple, but I'll

00:14:32.050 --> 00:14:35.110
show you a few applications that
you might not have thought of.

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:41.970
For example, suppose this is
true for every single security.

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:44.880
Well, if it's true for
every single security,

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:47.980
it turns out that this works
for portfolios as well.

00:14:47.980 --> 00:14:49.650
And let me show you why.

00:14:49.650 --> 00:14:51.510
Suppose you've got
a portfolio that's

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:54.150
a weighted average
of the returns

00:14:54.150 --> 00:14:57.680
for the individual
components securities.

00:14:57.680 --> 00:14:59.960
Then if I calculate
the covariance

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:03.920
between the portfolio return
and the tangency portfolio,

00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:08.110
or the market, the
covariance is going

00:15:08.110 --> 00:15:10.590
to look like this,
which is actually

00:15:10.590 --> 00:15:12.340
just going to look
like a weighted average

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:14.800
of the covariances.

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:19.060
This is a mathematical identity,
from here down to here.

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:22.360
And therefore, when
I divide both sides

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:26.170
by the variance of the market,
I get something pretty neat,

00:15:26.170 --> 00:15:29.800
which is that the
beta of my portfolio--

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:32.050
where beta is defined
as the covariance

00:15:32.050 --> 00:15:36.430
between the portfolio
and the market divided

00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:39.190
by the variance-- the
beta of the portfolio

00:15:39.190 --> 00:15:41.710
is just equal to the
weighted average of the betas

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:44.440
of my component securities.

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:47.340
That's really neat
because what that says

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:50.910
is that, when I want to measure
the risk of a collection

00:15:50.910 --> 00:15:54.510
of securities, as long
as I know the betas

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:58.350
of each individual
security, I can

00:15:58.350 --> 00:16:00.810
calculate a weighted
average of those betas.

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:03.800
And that is the beta
of my portfolio.

00:16:03.800 --> 00:16:07.200
So if you think of beta
as a measure of risk,

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:11.570
this measure of risk
is actually linear,

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:17.330
unlike volatility,
which is not linear.

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:21.140
The variance of a
portfolio is not simply

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:24.020
equal to the sum of
the variances weighted

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:25.370
by their portfolio weights.

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:27.650
It's that complicated
expression where

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:31.500
you're adding up all of
those cross products as well.

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:34.370
So we get an enormous
simplification

00:16:34.370 --> 00:16:35.960
with the security market line.

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:39.890
It says that we can measure
the risk of a portfolio using

00:16:39.890 --> 00:16:41.630
this concept called beta.

00:16:41.630 --> 00:16:44.090
And beta happens to
be linear in the sense

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:46.610
that, when you take
a weighted average,

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:48.590
the beta is equal to
the weighted average

00:16:48.590 --> 00:16:52.160
of the individual asset betas.

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:55.910
So therefore, if you
know that the betas are

00:16:55.910 --> 00:16:59.660
going to be a weighted
average, then, in fact,

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:03.020
the expected rate of
return on the portfolio

00:17:03.020 --> 00:17:05.210
now is equal to
the risk-free rate

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:12.470
plus this weighted average beta
times the market risk premium.

00:17:12.470 --> 00:17:13.800
Do you see the power of this?

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:17.730
This now allows you to
analyze the expected return

00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:21.210
on anything, any
collection of assets.

00:17:21.210 --> 00:17:23.940
If you know what the betas are
for the individual components,

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:25.939
you know what the betas
are for the whole thing.

00:17:29.210 --> 00:17:32.560
So now you can calculate the
appropriate rate of return

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:35.260
for virtually anything.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:37.400
And this is not just
limited to stocks.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:39.650
You can apply this to projects.

00:17:39.650 --> 00:17:41.320
For example, if you
want to know what

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:44.620
the expected rate of return
is on an oil drilling project,

00:17:44.620 --> 00:17:49.720
well, measure the beta of oil
drilling stocks, use that beta,

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:51.670
and that will be
appropriate discount

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:55.260
rate for that particular
oil drilling project.

00:17:55.260 --> 00:17:59.260
It's a really remarkable result.

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:02.740
So we have an expression for
the required rate of return,

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:05.560
opportunity cost of capital,
risk-adjusted discount rate,

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:09.130
for all the various different
kind of examples and cases

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:12.220
that we looked at up until now.

00:18:12.220 --> 00:18:14.980
And the last point I want
to make about this equation

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:18.640
is, how do you actually
take it out for a spin?

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:20.680
How do you estimate the
expected rate of return

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:22.250
on the market and
the risk-free rate?

00:18:22.250 --> 00:18:24.520
Well, that comes from the data.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:26.440
That comes from the marketplace.

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:28.720
We observe it in
the marketplace.

00:18:28.720 --> 00:18:30.870
And we can actually see it.

00:18:30.870 --> 00:18:31.480
OK.

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:34.240
So let's do some examples, just
to make sure that we all get

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:36.790
this and know how to apply it.

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:39.880
Using returns from
1990 to 2001, we

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:43.690
estimate that Microsoft's beta
during that period of time

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:46.180
is 1.49.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:49.090
And if you do the same
thing for Gillette,

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:52.930
you get that Gillette's
beta is 0.81.

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:57.430
Now, let's not even look
at the next set of numbers

00:18:57.430 --> 00:19:00.790
for a moment, and just talk
about those two numbers, 1.49

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:01.780
and 0.81.

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:03.310
Does that make sense to you?

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:05.240
Let's think about
what that's saying.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:09.820
1.49 says that the
covariance between Microsoft

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:13.510
and the market
portfolio is actually

00:19:13.510 --> 00:19:20.210
a lot higher than the
variance of the market itself.

00:19:20.210 --> 00:19:24.210
So let me ask you to
think about whether or not

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:26.820
adding Microsoft
to your portfolio

00:19:26.820 --> 00:19:29.760
is going to make it less
risky or more risky.

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:32.790
And here's how I want
you to think about it.

00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:35.550
Remember what we said
about diversification.

00:19:35.550 --> 00:19:37.920
When you hold a
collection of securities,

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:41.322
what matters more, the
variances or the covariances?

00:19:41.322 --> 00:19:42.352
AUDIENCE: Covariances.

00:19:42.352 --> 00:19:43.060
ANDREW LO: Right.

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:47.590
Why are the covariances
more important?

00:19:47.590 --> 00:19:51.700
What's a quick and dirty way
of arguing that the covariances

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:53.362
matter more?

00:19:53.362 --> 00:19:55.290
AUDIENCE: Because there
are n squared minus n.

00:19:55.290 --> 00:19:55.750
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:19:55.750 --> 00:19:57.550
There are a heck of a
lot more covariances

00:19:57.550 --> 00:19:58.591
than there are variances.

00:19:58.591 --> 00:20:01.040
You only got n variances
to worry about,

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:04.030
but you got n squared
minus n covariances.

00:20:04.030 --> 00:20:07.150
And if they all line up
in the same direction,

00:20:07.150 --> 00:20:10.570
you get the subprime
crisis problem, right?

00:20:10.570 --> 00:20:13.630
So covariances matter
more than variances.

00:20:13.630 --> 00:20:17.980
Well, if that's the case,
then when we look at a stock

00:20:17.980 --> 00:20:20.810
and think about bringing
it into our portfolio,

00:20:20.810 --> 00:20:23.080
we want to ask
the question, what

00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:29.070
is it doing in terms of adding
or subtracting covariances

00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:30.690
to our portfolio?

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:32.850
And one way to
measure whether or not

00:20:32.850 --> 00:20:36.600
it's adding or subtracting
is to ask the question, what

00:20:36.600 --> 00:20:42.870
is the covariance between
Microsoft and my stock

00:20:42.870 --> 00:20:43.800
holdings?

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:46.170
Now what are your
stock holdings?

00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:48.750
If everybody is a
rational investor--

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:52.020
by rational I mean
you like return

00:20:52.020 --> 00:20:53.700
and you don't like risk--

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:56.550
then you know you're going to
be holding the risk-free rate

00:20:56.550 --> 00:20:57.690
and the market portfolio.

00:20:57.690 --> 00:21:00.396
You're going to be on
that capital market line.

00:21:00.396 --> 00:21:01.770
So if you're a
rational investor,

00:21:01.770 --> 00:21:04.565
the only stock holding you
have is that mutual fund,

00:21:04.565 --> 00:21:07.230
m, the tangency portfolio.

00:21:07.230 --> 00:21:10.269
So therefore, the most
important thing in your mind

00:21:10.269 --> 00:21:12.060
is, when you think
about buying a new stock

00:21:12.060 --> 00:21:14.880
and putting into your
portfolio, is this

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:20.520
going to be highly correlated
with my market portfolio?

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:22.530
Well, that's what beta measures.

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:27.180
Beta is a relative measure that
says, OK, the total variance

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:29.390
that you're holding in
risky securities, that's

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:30.750
sigma m squared.

00:21:30.750 --> 00:21:35.070
That's the variance of
the market portfolio.

00:21:35.070 --> 00:21:39.200
How does Microsoft
compare to that

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:42.230
in terms of what
it will contribute,

00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:45.260
in terms of its covariance
with your holding?

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:47.039
So you're holding
one mutual fund,

00:21:47.039 --> 00:21:48.830
and you're thinking
about adding Microsoft.

00:21:48.830 --> 00:21:50.750
The only covariance that
you should care about

00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:52.700
is the covariance
between Microsoft

00:21:52.700 --> 00:21:54.810
and what you're holding.

00:21:54.810 --> 00:21:56.380
Well, that's what beta measures.

00:21:56.380 --> 00:21:58.570
If the number is greater
than 1, what it's saying

00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:01.750
is that, when you bring
Microsoft into your portfolio,

00:22:01.750 --> 00:22:04.480
you're going to be
increasing the variance

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:08.470
because the covariance,
which is what we care about,

00:22:08.470 --> 00:22:12.580
is greater than the variance
of what you're holding.

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:15.970
If, on the other hand,
the beta is less than 1,

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:19.120
then, presumably,
that's helping you

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:23.260
because that's lowering the
variance relative to what

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:24.280
you're holding.

00:22:24.280 --> 00:22:27.550
But helping or
hurting, that only

00:22:27.550 --> 00:22:30.340
can be answered
directly if you explain

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:34.130
what you're getting in terms
of the expected rate of return.

00:22:34.130 --> 00:22:37.540
So looking at beta by
itself is not enough.

00:22:37.540 --> 00:22:39.880
Beta is a measure of risk.

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:41.860
It measures this
covariance divided

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:45.280
by the variance, or
covariance per unit

00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:46.732
variance in the marketplace.

00:22:46.732 --> 00:22:48.940
But you want to know what
the expected rate of return

00:22:48.940 --> 00:22:49.440
is as well.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:52.070
That's what the security
market line gives you.

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:52.570
OK.

00:22:52.570 --> 00:22:54.490
Now let's get back
to the example.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:58.180
Microsoft is a lot more
risky than the market.

00:22:58.180 --> 00:23:02.120
It's about 49% more risky
according to this measure.

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:04.120
On the other hand,
Gillette is actually

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:06.950
less risky than the market.

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:09.050
Now do you guys buy that?

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:10.935
Does that pass the smell test?

00:23:10.935 --> 00:23:11.810
Does that make sense?

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:13.180
Why?

00:23:13.180 --> 00:23:17.125
What's the intuition for that?

00:23:17.125 --> 00:23:17.625
Courtney?

00:23:17.625 --> 00:23:19.958
AUDIENCE: Well, people don't
necessarily need computers.

00:23:19.958 --> 00:23:23.970
And the technology is variable,
but Gillette sells razor

00:23:23.970 --> 00:23:26.949
products and deodorant, which
is kind of a staple in a lot

00:23:26.949 --> 00:23:27.490
of people's--

00:23:27.490 --> 00:23:28.281
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:23:28.281 --> 00:23:28.880
That's right.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:34.080
If you make the argument that,
from 1990 to 2001, if there

00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:36.660
are economic downturns,
what's the first

00:23:36.660 --> 00:23:39.840
to go, razorblades or Windows?

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:40.800
Thankfully Windows.

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:45.390
Nowadays, I don't know the
answer to that actually.

00:23:45.390 --> 00:23:49.470
Because nowadays, we depend
so much on the internet,

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:51.210
that actually it
could be different.

00:23:51.210 --> 00:23:52.680
So I haven't updated
this analysis

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:56.940
to see what the beta
is from 2001 to 2008,

00:23:56.940 --> 00:23:59.170
but it could be different.

00:23:59.170 --> 00:24:00.900
So now we may have
unshaven geeks

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:03.090
that, you know,
during downturns--

00:24:03.090 --> 00:24:04.770
and maybe it's flipped around.

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:06.592
Eduard?

00:24:06.592 --> 00:24:08.300
AUDIENCE: Could you
give us an intuition?

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:11.040
Because beta allows
us to compute

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:15.890
the appropriate return
for a certain risk.

00:24:15.890 --> 00:24:16.840
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:19.010
AUDIENCE: But what
is the intuition of,

00:24:19.010 --> 00:24:23.147
how far away am I from
the efficiency portfolio?

00:24:23.147 --> 00:24:28.380
So, how bad is this portfolio
compared to the efficient one?

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:29.450
ANDREW LO: Yeah.

00:24:29.450 --> 00:24:31.401
So, that's a good question.

00:24:31.401 --> 00:24:33.650
Let me go back to this
equation and take a look at it,

00:24:33.650 --> 00:24:36.020
and try to provide even
more intuition for this

00:24:36.020 --> 00:24:37.490
before we go on.

00:24:37.490 --> 00:24:39.800
So the idea behind
this equation is

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:42.200
that it tells you that
this is the rate of return

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:46.570
that you should have if
you have a certain beta.

00:24:46.570 --> 00:24:50.130
Now you can actually measure
the deviation from that

00:24:50.130 --> 00:24:52.050
very simply by
asking the question.

00:24:52.050 --> 00:24:55.066
For a portfolio manager
or an investment project

00:24:55.066 --> 00:24:56.940
that yields an expected
rate of return that's

00:24:56.940 --> 00:25:00.220
different from this,
that difference

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:03.260
is actually what we call alpha.

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:05.550
And alpha could be
positive or negative.

00:25:05.550 --> 00:25:09.890
So when you say, how far
away are you from efficiency?

00:25:09.890 --> 00:25:12.487
This gives you a direct measure
of how far away you are.

00:25:12.487 --> 00:25:14.570
It's basically the difference
between the expected

00:25:14.570 --> 00:25:16.760
rate of return you
have versus what

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:20.900
you're supposed to have given
the beta of the security.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:22.740
But let me add one
more thing to that,

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:28.010
which is that beta is a measure
of a particular kind of risk

00:25:28.010 --> 00:25:31.520
that a particular security has.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:34.310
And the kind of risk,
as I said before,

00:25:34.310 --> 00:25:36.410
is this covariance
between the rate

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:41.240
of return on a particular
asset and the rate of return

00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:43.190
on the market portfolio.

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:46.760
This kind of risk is
not the total risk

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:48.770
of a particular security.

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:52.990
In fact, it is called
the systematic risk.

00:25:52.990 --> 00:25:55.730
The systematic
risk is the portion

00:25:55.730 --> 00:25:59.790
of the risk that is related
to the market portfolio.

00:25:59.790 --> 00:26:03.470
So how far away you are
from efficiency really

00:26:03.470 --> 00:26:08.660
depends upon how much
risk you have that is not

00:26:08.660 --> 00:26:11.270
necessarily systematic risk.

00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:13.504
Now, I don't expect you
to understand all of it

00:26:13.504 --> 00:26:15.920
yet because I need to develop
a little bit more machinery.

00:26:15.920 --> 00:26:17.720
But I'm going to get
back to that intuition

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:19.190
in just a few minutes, OK?

00:26:19.190 --> 00:26:20.060
So I'm going to
give you a better

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:22.490
answer to your question than
what I just did because I'll

00:26:22.490 --> 00:26:25.220
explain the difference
between systematic risk

00:26:25.220 --> 00:26:26.790
and idiosyncratic risk.

00:26:26.790 --> 00:26:29.780
And I think then it'll make
this completely transparent.

