00:29:51.250 --> 00:29:55.810
those assumptions each and every
time you use this technology.

00:29:55.810 --> 00:29:57.400
It's not physics.

00:29:57.400 --> 00:29:59.110
This is not mathematics.

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:01.930
You're applying a set of
theories and approximations

00:30:01.930 --> 00:30:03.952
to a much, much more
complex reality.

00:30:03.952 --> 00:30:05.410
Every time you
apply it, you've got

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:08.800
to go back and ask the
question, does it make sense?

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:10.510
Do these assumptions hold?

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:12.380
And if so, great,
go ahead and use it.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:15.430
If not, you've got to
go back and rederive

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:17.470
some of these analytics.

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:21.220
OK, so the security
market line is now

00:30:21.220 --> 00:30:24.230
a line that describes
the expected return,

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:27.880
or required rate of return,
on an asset or a project

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:31.180
as a function of the riskiness,
where the riskiness is now

00:30:31.180 --> 00:30:33.640
measured by beta, not by sigma.

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:36.550
It's not variance or
standard deviation

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:42.510
that measures the appropriate
risk for most projects.

00:30:42.510 --> 00:30:45.390
Most projects, the way
you measure their risk

00:30:45.390 --> 00:30:47.900
is not by sigma.

00:30:47.900 --> 00:30:50.180
It turns out that the way
you measure their risk,

00:30:50.180 --> 00:30:54.410
for the purposes of calculating
the required rate of return,

00:30:54.410 --> 00:30:58.010
you measure it by beta.

00:30:58.010 --> 00:30:59.240
OK?

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:01.970
That's a very deep insight.

00:31:01.970 --> 00:31:04.580
It changes the way
we think about risk

00:31:04.580 --> 00:31:05.900
and expected rate of return.

00:31:05.900 --> 00:31:09.175
It's not to say that risk,
in terms of volatility,

00:31:09.175 --> 00:31:09.800
doesn't matter.

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:11.000
Of course it does.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.460
That is the basis of
this entire framework.

00:31:13.460 --> 00:31:16.400
We started out by saying
that people don't like sigma,

00:31:16.400 --> 00:31:18.350
and they do like mu.

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:19.400
They don't like variants.

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:21.320
They do like expected
rate of return.

00:31:21.320 --> 00:31:22.850
That still holds.

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:26.900
But in doing so, when we derive
all of these implications, what

00:31:26.900 --> 00:31:30.680
we find is that,
as an investor, you

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:34.970
don't get rewarded for taking
larger and larger amounts

00:31:34.970 --> 00:31:38.000
of volatility necessarily.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.260
You do get rewarded for taking
larger and larger amounts

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:43.700
of beta.

00:31:43.700 --> 00:31:48.200
That's the sense in which beta
is a better measure of risk.

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:52.010
For the purposes of computing
the required rate of return,

00:31:52.010 --> 00:31:54.980
beta is the right
measurement, not sigma.

00:31:54.980 --> 00:31:59.120
The only cases where sigma is
the right measure of risk--

00:31:59.120 --> 00:32:03.620
when I say right, I mean where
increases in sigma must imply

00:32:03.620 --> 00:32:07.020
increases in the
required rate of return--

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:09.580
is when?

00:32:09.580 --> 00:32:11.990
When is sigma the
right measure of risk

00:32:11.990 --> 00:32:16.920
for the purposes of computing
the required rate of return?

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:19.620
For what kind of
securities or portfolios?

00:32:22.450 --> 00:32:22.962
Yeah?

00:32:22.962 --> 00:32:24.670
AUDIENCE: Is it for
efficient portfolios?

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:25.461
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:32:25.461 --> 00:32:28.000
For efficient portfolios only.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:33.130
Efficient portfolios meaning
these guys, meaning these guys.

00:32:33.130 --> 00:32:37.600
Anything on this line, then
sigma is the right measure.

00:32:37.600 --> 00:32:44.700
Sigma p over sigma m, that is
the right measure for any kind

00:32:44.700 --> 00:32:47.640
of portfolio that is efficient.

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.760
But we know that the
typical security,

00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:54.650
the typical project, the typical
division, is not efficient.

00:32:54.650 --> 00:32:57.870
Efficient, again,
meaning you can get the--

00:32:57.870 --> 00:33:00.660
you can't get any better
expected rate of return

00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:04.320
for the same risk, or you can't
get a lower amount of risk

00:33:04.320 --> 00:33:06.460
for the same expected
rate of return.

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:10.740
So for all of the inefficient
securities, portfolios,

00:33:10.740 --> 00:33:13.770
or projects, you've got
to use this relationship,

00:33:13.770 --> 00:33:16.690
and this relationship tells
you beta is what matters,

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:17.700
not sigma.

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:21.000
Sigma is not the same as
beta, except if you happen

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:24.910
to be an efficient portfolio.

00:33:24.910 --> 00:33:25.654
OK.

00:33:25.654 --> 00:33:27.070
Question-- do you
