that shows that the relationship
between risk and expected

00:39:30.150 --> 00:39:37.170
return, where risk is measured
by beta now, is linear.

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:39.370
This is a linear relationship.

00:39:39.370 --> 00:39:43.440
So this is a major advance
that we didn't expect.

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:47.410
And, in fact, so what I showed
before was the preferences.

00:39:47.410 --> 00:39:50.880
So in other words, we talked
last time about the situation

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:54.630
where, suppose that
you're an investor,

00:39:54.630 --> 00:39:57.990
and I start you off
at a point like this.

00:39:57.990 --> 00:40:00.570
And I ask the
question, if I want

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:05.580
you to tell me where
you're going to be such

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:07.580
that you're just as well off.

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:10.250
You have the same
level of utility.

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:12.270
That curve, that
indifference curve,

00:40:12.270 --> 00:40:15.870
is going to look
something like this.

00:40:15.870 --> 00:40:17.520
That's going to be curved.

00:40:17.520 --> 00:40:19.580
That's what you're
talking about.

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:23.720
But that's the behavior
of one individual.

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:25.380
The point about the
CAPM is that if you

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:29.820
aggregate all of the individuals
together and ask the question,

00:40:29.820 --> 00:40:33.120
what does the expected rate
of return and volatility

00:40:33.120 --> 00:40:35.850
or expected rate of
return and beta look like?

00:40:35.850 --> 00:40:37.270
How are they related?

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:41.280
In fact, it's magical that
it actually is linear.

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:45.360
So it's exactly the fact that
we didn't expect linearity.

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:48.120
Given that there are
diminishing marginal returns

00:40:48.120 --> 00:40:51.930
to risk and reward, you
wouldn't expect linearity.

00:40:51.930 --> 00:40:53.850
But, in fact, it drops out.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:58.320
I mean, this drops out of this
tangency portfolio argument,

00:40:58.320 --> 00:40:59.660
right?

00:40:59.660 --> 00:41:01.410
Nothing up my sleeve,
this was an argument

00:41:01.410 --> 00:41:02.460
that we all did together.

00:41:02.460 --> 00:41:05.790
And we derived this curve
from first principles.

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:10.230
So this is really an
astounding result,

00:41:10.230 --> 00:41:12.180
but it's even more
astonishing that you

00:41:12.180 --> 00:41:14.370
get this result
for all securities,

00:41:14.370 --> 00:41:18.570
not just for
efficient portfolios.

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:22.170
OK, other questions?

00:41:22.170 --> 00:41:22.980
All right.

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:24.970
Let's do another example.

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:30.010
So here I want to show you how
you can use the security market

00:41:30.010 --> 00:41:33.950
line, also called
the CAPM, C-A-P-M,

00:41:33.950 --> 00:41:36.339
for Capital Asset Pricing Model.

00:41:36.339 --> 00:41:37.880
I want to show you
how you can use it

00:41:37.880 --> 00:41:39.900
to do performance attribution.

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:43.460
This is the data from
a real live hedge fund

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:46.250
manager, who will go nameless
since I don't want to get

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:48.680
sued by him for any reason.

00:41:48.680 --> 00:41:52.520
Hedge fund managers are both
very wealthy, typically,

00:41:52.520 --> 00:41:55.610
and also very
litigious, so you want

00:41:55.610 --> 00:41:58.520
to be careful when you
talk about them in public.

00:41:58.520 --> 00:42:02.960
Hedge fund XYZ had an average
annualized return of 12.5%

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:06.080
and a return standard
deviation of 5.5% from January

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:11.660
'85 to December 2002, and the
estimated beta over this period

00:42:11.660 --> 00:42:13.840
was minus 0.028.

00:42:13.840 --> 00:42:15.590
Now, somebody asked
about a negative beta.

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:19.540
Well here's an example
of a negative beta asset.

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:23.960
Positive expected rate
of return, negative beta.

00:42:23.960 --> 00:42:25.900
So if it's got a
positive expected return

00:42:25.900 --> 00:42:28.270
and a negative beta, you
know something can't exactly

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:31.840
be right because that doesn't
sound like it makes sense

00:42:31.840 --> 00:42:34.440
in terms of the CAPM framework.

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:35.940
And, in fact, it doesn't.

00:42:35.940 --> 00:42:37.390
It doesn't make sense.

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:39.510
Well, let's do the math.

00:42:39.510 --> 00:42:41.370
The expected the
rate of return is

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:45.000
equal to Rf plus beta times
the market risk premium.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:48.300
Market risk premium of
6%, risk-free rate of 5%,

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:50.430
plug that in with the
beta of minus 0.028,

00:42:50.430 --> 00:42:53.730
and you get that
this manager should

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:57.940
have earned 4.83% per year.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:01.560
That's what the manager
should have earned.

00:43:01.560 --> 00:43:07.380
In fact, the manager earned
a rate of return of 12.%

00:43:07.380 --> 00:43:09.040
per year.

00:43:09.040 --> 00:43:10.590
So that's an alpha.

00:43:10.590 --> 00:43:14.880
If you define the alpha as
what the manager did earn minus

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:17.520
what the manager
should have earned,

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:23.230
you've got an alpha of
771 basis points per year.

00:43:23.230 --> 00:43:26.470
That's a humongous alpha.

00:43:26.470 --> 00:43:31.420
Very, very big amount
of excess performance.

00:43:31.420 --> 00:43:34.010
This is why people are
excited about hedge funds.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:37.120
Now, we're not going to talk
in great detail about it

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:40.780
in this course because it goes
beyond the scope of Finance

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:42.520
401.

00:43:42.520 --> 00:43:45.999
But in an investments
course, the next level

00:43:45.999 --> 00:43:48.040
of sophistication would
be to take a look at this

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:51.940
and say, OK, is this
alpha really alpha,

00:43:51.940 --> 00:43:57.331
or is it due to other factors,
other risks that we're not

00:43:57.331 --> 00:43:57.830
measuring?

00:43:57.830 --> 00:44:00.200
Right now the only
risk we're measuring

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:06.070
is this tangency portfolio
risk, this beta risk.

00:44:06.070 --> 00:44:08.360
But maybe there are
multiple betas out there.

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:10.360
We're not going to talk
about it in this course,

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:11.960
but in 433 you will discuss it.

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:13.940
And it will turn out
that hedge funds actually

00:44:13.940 --> 00:44:15.719
do have multiple betas.

00:44:15.719 --> 00:44:18.260
So you shouldn't go out and put
all your money in hedge funds

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:21.320
right away because this
extra performance, some of it

00:44:21.320 --> 00:44:28.207
is due to true genius and
insight and unique skill.

00:44:28.207 --> 00:44:29.790
But part of it is
also due to the fact

00:44:29.790 --> 00:44:33.570
that you're bearing risks that
you had no idea you're bearing.

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:36.360
And so you've got to be careful
about getting on the bandwagon

00:44:36.360 --> 00:44:38.190
and saying, yeah, give
me some hedge funds.

00:44:38.190 --> 00:44:39.670
I want some of this alpha.

00:44:39.670 --> 00:44:41.439
Anon?

00:44:41.439 --> 00:44:46.891
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
But how do we know

00:44:46.891 --> 00:44:48.210
this is good for the investor?

00:44:48.210 --> 00:44:52.174
Because they could have invested
in the asset [INAUDIBLE]..

00:44:52.174 --> 00:44:53.840
ANDREW LO: So the
question is, how do we

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:56.120
know that this is actually
good for the investor?

00:44:56.120 --> 00:45:00.470
Because they could have gotten
some returns from the S&amp;P.

00:45:00.470 --> 00:45:03.210
The way we know that
is because we're

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:08.860
measuring the expected rate
of return relative to the S&amp;P.

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:11.310
So in other words, the
way I got this number,

00:45:11.310 --> 00:45:14.190
this is the excess
return on the S&amp;P.

00:45:14.190 --> 00:45:16.440
That's what the market
risk premium is.

00:45:16.440 --> 00:45:21.790
So in fact, given the
beta of this manager,

00:45:21.790 --> 00:45:25.960
it should have only
given you 4.83%

00:45:25.960 --> 00:45:29.590
return relative to what the
S&amp;P would have given you,

00:45:29.590 --> 00:45:33.290
which is a 6% excess
rate of return.

00:45:33.290 --> 00:45:37.820
And, in fact, what we see is
that this manager produced

00:45:37.820 --> 00:45:41.450
a 12% rate of
return, or 7% above

00:45:41.450 --> 00:45:44.990
and beyond what it was
supposed to have done.

00:45:44.990 --> 00:45:46.796
So this takes that into account.

00:45:46.796 --> 00:45:48.170
What it doesn't
take into account

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:51.650
is how much liquidity risk the
hedge fund manager is taking,

00:45:51.650 --> 00:45:55.770
how much currency risk,
how much commodity risk,

00:45:55.770 --> 00:45:58.530
and a bunch of other risks
that are not represented

00:45:58.530 --> 00:46:01.060
by the tangency portfolio.

00:46:01.060 --> 00:46:02.771
Megan?

00:46:02.771 --> 00:46:05.256
AUDIENCE:
[? When you hear about ?]

00:46:05.256 --> 00:46:07.490
looking out for beta
dressed up as alpha,

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.877
it's really because there
are multiple sources of beta

00:46:10.877 --> 00:46:12.460
that aren't getting
wrapped into that.

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:13.330
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:46:13.330 --> 00:46:14.440
That's exactly right.

00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:16.570
Recently, a lot of
institutional investors

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:18.220
have become skeptical
of hedge funds

00:46:18.220 --> 00:46:21.760
because they say,
hedge funds alpha

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:24.110
is really dressed up data.

00:46:24.110 --> 00:46:25.870
In other words,
hedge fund managers

00:46:25.870 --> 00:46:27.820
are taking risks
that are not captured

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:29.546
by this very simple framework.

00:46:29.546 --> 00:46:31.420
And so when you run
these kind of regressions

00:46:31.420 --> 00:46:34.210
and do this analysis, you're
getting tremendous alpha,

00:46:34.210 --> 00:46:36.630
but in fact, it's not all alpha.

00:46:36.630 --> 00:46:40.040
There's other kinds
of betas in there.

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:41.620
And so there's a
whole literature

00:46:41.620 --> 00:46:44.020
that has developed
about multiple,

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:47.020
what are called exotic,
betas or alternative betas.

00:46:47.020 --> 00:46:49.750
Again, not part of the
scope of introductory

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:53.193
finance, but it is something
that's covered in investments.

00:46:57.060 --> 00:47:01.950
Just another illustration of
what this hedge fund has done.

00:47:01.950 --> 00:47:04.950
Take a look at the
growth of $1 invested

00:47:04.950 --> 00:47:08.760
in the hedge fund over
the last 20 years,

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:11.130
and you'll see that the
blue line is the hedge fund.

00:47:11.130 --> 00:47:13.270
The red line is the S&amp;P 500.

00:47:13.270 --> 00:47:18.224
So to your point, Anon, the
S&amp;P 500 gave you a wild ride.

00:47:18.224 --> 00:47:19.890
And so for a while
you were doing better

00:47:19.890 --> 00:47:23.100
than the hedge fund, but,
in fact, now this hedge fund

00:47:23.100 --> 00:47:24.660
has done quite a bit better.

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:27.744
Now this ends in 2002.

00:47:27.744 --> 00:47:29.410
I'll give you a little
bit of an update.

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:31.400
I don't have it
