00:47:59.110 --> 00:48:00.060
Yeah?

00:48:00.060 --> 00:48:04.335
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] The
risk-free rate is changing.

00:48:04.335 --> 00:48:07.737
The market rate
is changing, so--

00:48:07.737 --> 00:48:08.320
ANDREW LO: No.

00:48:08.320 --> 00:48:10.280
In fact, everything is changing.

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:12.931
So if you want to
take seriously change,

00:48:12.931 --> 00:48:15.430
you've basically got to figure
out how the risk-free rate is

00:48:15.430 --> 00:48:17.920
changing, the expected
rate of return is changing,

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:21.424
and the betas actually
are also changing.

00:48:21.424 --> 00:48:23.590
But what I'm trying to do
with a simple illustration

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:26.850
is use a long period and
say, over that entire period,

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:29.270
let's average across
all of these changes.

00:48:29.270 --> 00:48:30.008
Justin?

00:48:30.008 --> 00:48:35.424
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
If you look at the graph

00:48:35.424 --> 00:48:38.612
and it seems like the
differences of the graph

00:48:38.612 --> 00:48:40.540
were just higher
with the market.

00:48:40.540 --> 00:48:43.660
ANDREW LO: It is, but you
don't adjust for the beta.

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:45.460
That's the key, right?

00:48:45.460 --> 00:48:47.930
The S&amp;P has a beta of 1.

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:49.910
This guy, this
hedge fund manager,

00:48:49.910 --> 00:48:53.150
has a beta of 0 or
slightly negative.

00:48:53.150 --> 00:48:54.680
That's the difference.

00:48:54.680 --> 00:48:58.190
That's why looking at
volatility can be misleading.

00:48:58.190 --> 00:48:59.750
If you look at
volatility, you'd say,

00:48:59.750 --> 00:49:03.000
well, you know, obviously
the S&amp;P has done better.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:08.750
But keep in mind that look
how smooth the blue line is.

00:49:08.750 --> 00:49:13.670
And the lesson of the
CAPM is that investors

00:49:13.670 --> 00:49:17.930
pay for smoothness, but only
a certain kind of smoothness.

00:49:17.930 --> 00:49:21.290
In other words, smoothness
means low volatility, right?

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:23.690
The smoothest line,
of course, is T-bills.

00:49:23.690 --> 00:49:24.830
That's a straight line.

00:49:24.830 --> 00:49:28.340
That will go sort of like this.

00:49:28.340 --> 00:49:30.680
And investors are not
going to pay a lot for that

00:49:30.680 --> 00:49:34.280
because that doesn't
really help them generate

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:36.020
expected rate of return.

00:49:36.020 --> 00:49:39.290
If you've got expected rate of
return and smoothness together,

00:49:39.290 --> 00:49:42.270
you get a really big, big alpha.

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:45.620
And that's exactly what we see
here, an alpha of 771 basis

00:49:45.620 --> 00:49:46.120
points.

00:49:48.950 --> 00:49:51.580
Now, here I talk about
these multiple sources

00:49:51.580 --> 00:49:53.410
of systematic risk.

00:49:53.410 --> 00:49:55.630
I don't want to focus
on that for this course

00:49:55.630 --> 00:49:58.360
because, as I said, it's going
to be much more complicated

00:49:58.360 --> 00:50:00.710
and requires more machinery.

00:50:00.710 --> 00:50:03.730
But the basic
intuition is the same.

00:50:03.730 --> 00:50:08.270
Instead of just one
source of systematic risk,

00:50:08.270 --> 00:50:09.554
you may have multiple sources.

00:50:09.554 --> 00:50:11.720
And so therefore, you're
going to have multiple risk

00:50:11.720 --> 00:50:14.550
premia as opposed to just one.

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:17.450
But for now, let's
not focus on that.

00:50:17.450 --> 00:50:19.310
And we're going to
focus our attention just

00:50:19.310 --> 00:50:22.289
on this simple equation, and
make sure we understand it

00:50:22.289 --> 00:50:23.330
and know how to apply it.

00:50:26.290 --> 00:50:27.690
Now, I want to go--

00:50:27.690 --> 00:50:32.320
I want to give you one
more intuition for why

00:50:32.320 --> 00:50:36.670
it is that beta is the
appropriate measure of risk,

00:50:36.670 --> 00:50:41.500
and not sigma, for arbitrary
inefficient portfolios.

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:44.470
And the idea is
actually pretty simple.

00:50:44.470 --> 00:50:46.990
When you think of an
investment like Microsoft

00:50:46.990 --> 00:50:51.280
or like Gillette, you can think
of the risk of that portfolio

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:52.270
as being--

00:50:52.270 --> 00:50:55.690
the risk of that investment
in those individual securities

00:50:55.690 --> 00:50:57.650
as having two components.

00:50:57.650 --> 00:51:00.580
So when you think of the
volatility of Gillette,

00:51:00.580 --> 00:51:02.890
you can think of the
volatility of Gillette

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:05.730
coming from two sources.

00:51:05.730 --> 00:51:15.340
One source is the aggregate
risk that affects all companies.

00:51:15.340 --> 00:51:17.380
And the second source
of risk is the risk

00:51:17.380 --> 00:51:19.630
unique to Gillette,
the fact that they've

00:51:19.630 --> 00:51:22.750
got a particular manufacturing
plant in a particular location

00:51:22.750 --> 00:51:24.310
of the country, the
fact that they've

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:27.880
got a specific set of managers
that are either good or bad,

00:51:27.880 --> 00:51:29.680
the fact that they
are subject to a very

00:51:29.680 --> 00:51:33.310
specific set of requirements
for producing their blades,

00:51:33.310 --> 00:51:37.100
who knows, but very
specific to that company.

00:51:37.100 --> 00:51:41.900
When you think about
that kind of risk,

00:51:41.900 --> 00:51:45.620
let me ask you a question from
a purely business perspective.

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:46.790
You're the investor.

00:51:46.790 --> 00:51:48.500
I'm a representative
of Gillette.

00:51:48.500 --> 00:51:50.810
I'm trying to sell you
my company's stock.

00:51:50.810 --> 00:51:54.600
I want you to invest
in my company.

00:51:54.600 --> 00:52:00.850
And therefore, I have to pay you
to take the risk of Gillette.

00:52:00.850 --> 00:52:04.490
If I tell you that Gillette
has these two pieces of risk--

00:52:04.490 --> 00:52:08.380
so I'm the representative from
Gillette and I tell you that

00:52:08.380 --> 00:52:12.190
our company is subject to
economy-wide fluctuations that

00:52:12.190 --> 00:52:17.350
will help or hurt our business
and unique fluctuations that

00:52:17.350 --> 00:52:22.490
are specific and
special to Gillette--

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:25.100
which of these two
risks are you going

00:52:25.100 --> 00:52:29.000
to be more concerned about
from your investment portfolio

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.050
perspective?

00:52:31.050 --> 00:52:31.550
Rami?

00:52:31.550 --> 00:52:34.310
AUDIENCE: I think you'd
be more concerned about--

00:52:34.310 --> 00:52:36.610
as a portfolio as a whole,
you look at the economy,

00:52:36.610 --> 00:52:38.611
but I think, for this
specific purpose,

00:52:38.611 --> 00:52:41.710
[INAUDIBLE] you obviously
will pick Gillette-specific--

00:52:41.710 --> 00:52:42.640
ANDREW LO: OK.

00:52:42.640 --> 00:52:45.110
But I want-- you hurried
through the first point,

00:52:45.110 --> 00:52:47.180
and I want you to expand
on that a little bit.

00:52:47.180 --> 00:52:50.480
You said that if you're worried
about your portfolio, then

00:52:50.480 --> 00:52:52.190
obviously the economy-wide risk.

00:52:52.190 --> 00:52:53.162
AUDIENCE: Absolutely.

00:52:53.162 --> 00:52:56.564
If you're worried about
the economy-wide risk,

00:52:56.564 --> 00:52:58.994
and for example, over the
next two, three years,

00:52:58.994 --> 00:53:01.157
you don't think the economy
is going to recover,

00:53:01.157 --> 00:53:03.900
then you're going to just
avoid that type of investment

00:53:03.900 --> 00:53:04.440
as a whole.

00:53:04.440 --> 00:53:05.790
ANDREW LO: OK.

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:06.834
OK, fine.

00:53:06.834 --> 00:53:09.000
But on the other hand, you
also said something else,

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:11.730
which is that if you're
comparing between two stocks,

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:13.950
then what you're focusing
on is the risks that

00:53:13.950 --> 00:53:15.756
are unique to Gillette.

00:53:15.756 --> 00:53:20.193
AUDIENCE: You also might look at
how much the economic downturn

00:53:20.193 --> 00:53:22.350
would affect a
company like Gillette.

00:53:22.350 --> 00:53:23.066
ANDREW LO: Right.

00:53:23.066 --> 00:53:25.482
AUDIENCE: So if the economic
downturn, as you said before,

00:53:25.482 --> 00:53:28.815
affects Microsoft greater
than it would Gillette,

00:53:28.815 --> 00:53:30.689
and you suspect something
is going to happen,

00:53:30.689 --> 00:53:32.154
you'd go for Gillette.

00:53:32.154 --> 00:53:34.112
If, on the other hand,
you didn't suspect that,

00:53:34.112 --> 00:53:35.590
you might go for--

00:53:35.590 --> 00:53:36.210
ANDREW LO: OK.

00:53:36.210 --> 00:53:38.670
But let's now talk
about the negotiations

00:53:38.670 --> 00:53:39.780
between you and me.

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:41.160
I'm a representative
of Gillette.

00:53:41.160 --> 00:53:43.370
I'm trying to get you
to invest with us.

00:53:43.370 --> 00:53:45.330
And I've got two
sources of risk that you

00:53:45.330 --> 00:53:51.500
might be concerned about, market
risk or Gillette-specific risk.

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:53.990
From your portfolio
perspective, since you just

00:53:53.990 --> 00:53:57.271
care about maximizing the
value of your portfolio,

00:53:57.271 --> 00:53:59.270
you're not worried about
Gillette in particular.

00:53:59.270 --> 00:54:00.290
You're not management.

00:54:00.290 --> 00:54:01.250
You're an investor.

00:54:01.250 --> 00:54:02.210
I'm management.

00:54:02.210 --> 00:54:03.410
I'm worried about Gillette.

00:54:03.410 --> 00:54:06.380
I couldn't care less about your
portfolio, I'm sorry to say.

00:54:06.380 --> 00:54:09.680
What I care about is my
company, but what you care about

00:54:09.680 --> 00:54:10.910
is your portfolio.

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:13.340
From your portfolio
perspective, what

00:54:13.340 --> 00:54:17.030
are you going to care more
about, Gillette-specific risk

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:22.495
or the macroeconomic risk that
I represent to your portfolio?

00:54:22.495 --> 00:54:23.950
AUDIENCE: When I'm
talking to you,

00:54:23.950 --> 00:54:26.380
I care more about
your specific risks.

00:54:26.380 --> 00:54:28.840
ANDREW LO: Well, I'm
asking a question though

00:54:28.840 --> 00:54:29.927
about your portfolio.

00:54:29.927 --> 00:54:31.510
What you care about
is your portfolio.

00:54:31.510 --> 00:54:33.070
I understand that when
you're talking to me,

00:54:33.070 --> 00:54:35.528
you're going to be asking me
about my company-specific risk

00:54:35.528 --> 00:54:36.940
to try to get a handle on it.

00:54:36.940 --> 00:54:38.920
But is that what
you ultimately are

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:40.151
going to be concerned about?

00:54:40.151 --> 00:54:42.150
AUDIENCE: I would be
concerned about, obviously,

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:46.237
the macro portion of it
and how you fit into that.

00:54:46.237 --> 00:54:49.109
But I'd look at
your beta and see--

00:54:49.109 --> 00:54:50.900
ANDREW LO: You don't
know the CAPM, though.

00:54:50.900 --> 00:54:55.460
So now you're cheating
because you now know the CAPM.

00:54:55.460 --> 00:54:56.630
But suppose you didn't.

00:54:56.630 --> 00:54:58.450
What I'm trying to get
at is the intuition,

00:54:58.450 --> 00:55:00.890
a businessman's
intuition, for what

00:55:00.890 --> 00:55:03.110
you would care
about more in terms

00:55:03.110 --> 00:55:05.810
of what I do to your portfolio.

00:55:05.810 --> 00:55:06.530
Yeah, Sema?

00:55:06.530 --> 00:55:08.362
AUDIENCE: Didn't you
say, two lectures ago,

00:55:08.362 --> 00:55:11.570
that the idiosyncratic risk
is [? their survival? ?]

00:55:11.570 --> 00:55:12.305
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:55:12.305 --> 00:55:14.430
AUDIENCE: So, you care more
about systematic risk--

00:55:14.430 --> 00:55:14.790
ANDREW LO: Why?

00:55:14.790 --> 00:55:16.910
AUDIENCE: Because only one
[INAUDIBLE] in my portfolio.

00:55:16.910 --> 00:55:18.350
ANDREW LO: That's exactly right.

00:55:18.350 --> 00:55:21.860
The idea is that if
it's Gillette-specific

00:55:21.860 --> 00:55:24.980
risk, then by
definition, if you're

00:55:24.980 --> 00:55:28.150
holding a well-diversified
portfolio,

00:55:28.150 --> 00:55:30.760
then you're not going to care
about that because that's going

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:33.100
to average out to nothing.

00:55:33.100 --> 00:55:36.040
Now, of course, we have
to think about the case

00:55:36.040 --> 00:55:38.260
where you're not holding
a diversified portfolio,

00:55:38.260 --> 00:55:40.390
but let me get back
to that in a minute.

00:55:40.390 --> 00:55:42.849
I'm assuming that all of you
are good business folks, which

00:55:42.849 --> 00:55:44.390
means that you're
going to be holding

00:55:44.390 --> 00:55:45.500
a diversified portfolio.

00:55:45.500 --> 00:55:47.770
You're not going to
concentrate all your bets

00:55:47.770 --> 00:55:52.150
on one particular kind
of investment, right?

00:55:52.150 --> 00:55:55.060
So if you are already holding
a very well-diversified

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:57.970
portfolio, then when
you interview me

00:55:57.970 --> 00:56:01.960
as a potential
investment opportunity,

00:56:01.960 --> 00:56:04.870
do you really care about
the idiosyncratic risk?

00:56:04.870 --> 00:56:07.360
Because that risk is going
to be diversified away.

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:09.760
What you care about from a
portfolio perspective is,

00:56:09.760 --> 00:56:12.250
how much am I going
to be contributing

00:56:12.250 --> 00:56:14.140
to your overall risk?

00:56:14.140 --> 00:56:18.520
And now that you know the CAPM,
you understand the logic of it.

00:56:18.520 --> 00:56:23.080
It says, you care about my beta
because my beta is a measure

00:56:23.080 --> 00:56:26.320
of the amount of risk I'm going
to be adding to your portfolio

00:56:26.320 --> 00:56:28.180
that you cannot get rid of.

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:30.910
How do you know you
cannot get rid of it?

00:56:30.910 --> 00:56:33.840
Well, by definition it's
the market portfolio.

00:56:33.840 --> 00:56:34.950
Everybody's holding it.

00:56:34.950 --> 00:56:37.480
Nobody wants to get
rid of it completely.

00:56:37.480 --> 00:56:40.170
You're on the capital
market's line.

00:56:40.170 --> 00:56:41.910
That's the best you can do.

00:56:41.910 --> 00:56:47.100
So this notion of
firm-specific risk

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:50.100
versus economy-wide
risk, that distinction

00:56:50.100 --> 00:56:51.690
is a really important one.

00:56:51.690 --> 00:56:54.190
And I'll show you the
mathematics of it in a minute,

00:56:54.190 --> 00:56:56.410
but I want to give
you the intuition.

00:56:56.410 --> 00:56:59.490
As a result, think
about this conversation

00:56:59.490 --> 00:57:02.100
happening not just for
Gillette, but for every company

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:03.720
in the economy.

00:57:03.720 --> 00:57:07.680
If it's the case that portfolio
managers that are buying stocks

00:57:07.680 --> 00:57:12.490
only care about the systematic
risk, about the market risk,

00:57:12.490 --> 00:57:15.640
about the risk that they cannot
get rid of, and then you have

00:57:15.640 --> 00:57:18.850
to reward them for that, then
what that means is that you

00:57:18.850 --> 00:57:23.850
don't have to reward them
for idiosyncratic risk.

00:57:23.850 --> 00:57:24.480
Why?

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:26.934
Because that's not risk
that you are forced to bear.

00:57:26.934 --> 00:57:28.350
There's nothing
that says you have

00:57:28.350 --> 00:57:30.672
to bear idiosyncratic risk.

00:57:30.672 --> 00:57:32.130
How do you get rid
of idiosyncratic

00:57:32.130 --> 00:57:35.160
risk if you don't
want to bear it?

00:57:35.160 --> 00:57:35.790
Diversify.

00:57:35.790 --> 00:57:36.660
Exactly.

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:38.610
Just buy 10 stocks
instead of one,

00:57:38.610 --> 00:57:39.830
and then you're diversified.

00:57:39.830 --> 00:57:41.940
20 stocks is better than 10.

00:57:41.940 --> 00:57:45.390
And mathematically,
after 50 stocks,

00:57:45.390 --> 00:57:47.040
you're basically diversified.

00:57:47.040 --> 00:57:48.600
You're done.

00:57:48.600 --> 00:57:53.190
So nobody should be holding
two or three stocks.

00:57:53.190 --> 00:57:58.855
Or if they do, they are bearing
risk that they need not bear.

00:57:58.855 --> 00:58:00.730
And they may want to do
it for other reasons.

00:58:00.730 --> 00:58:03.900
For example, as a
manager of Gillette,

00:58:03.900 --> 00:58:05.730
I believe in the company.

00:58:05.730 --> 00:58:07.530
I want to demonstrate
to my shareholders

00:58:07.530 --> 00:58:09.600
that I'm tied to
the company, so I'm

00:58:09.600 --> 00:58:12.090
going to hold a lot of my
wealth in Gillette stock.

00:58:12.090 --> 00:58:13.740
That's not well diversified.

00:58:13.740 --> 00:58:17.310
I'm holding a lot of
Gillette-specific risk.

00:58:17.310 --> 00:58:19.530
That's not a smart thing
to do from an investment

00:58:19.530 --> 00:58:21.300
point of view, but
that is a smart thing

00:58:21.300 --> 00:58:23.430
to do from a management
point of view

00:58:23.430 --> 00:58:28.480
because I'm tying my fate
to the fate of the company.

00:58:28.480 --> 00:58:32.130
It's definitely not a smart
thing from an investments

00:58:32.130 --> 00:58:33.330
perspective.

00:58:33.330 --> 00:58:35.100
If you're in a financial
services sector,

00:58:35.100 --> 00:58:38.096
you should not be buying
financial services stocks.

00:58:38.096 --> 00:58:39.720
If you're in the
pharmaceutical sector,

00:58:39.720 --> 00:58:42.090
you should not be
buying biotech stocks.

00:58:42.090 --> 00:58:47.220
And yet we do that for
reasons other than portfolio

00:58:47.220 --> 00:58:48.600
management.

00:58:48.600 --> 00:58:51.454
But given that I'm teaching
you about portfolio management,

00:58:51.454 --> 00:58:53.370
I'm not going to focus
on those other reasons.

00:58:53.370 --> 00:58:56.062
If this were an
organizational studies course,

00:58:56.062 --> 00:58:57.770
you'd be getting a
different perspective.

00:58:57.770 --> 00:58:59.740
And you should get a
different perspective.

00:58:59.740 --> 00:59:02.250
But for the purposes of
building financial wealth, what

00:59:02.250 --> 00:59:04.500
you want to do is
to focus on how

00:59:04.500 --> 00:59:07.950
much the systematic component
is contributing to your risk,

00:59:07.950 --> 00:59:10.290
because the
idiosyncratic component

00:59:10.290 --> 00:59:11.970
you don't have to bear.

00:59:11.970 --> 00:59:12.977
Yeah?

00:59:12.977 --> 00:59:15.101
AUDIENCE: So like an employee
purchase plan, where,

00:59:15.101 --> 00:59:15.737
if you're in financial
services, you're

00:59:15.737 --> 00:59:17.153
working for a
mutual fund company,

00:59:17.153 --> 00:59:19.800
and they offer you 10%,
15% you put your salary in,

00:59:19.800 --> 00:59:20.855
and you can buy stock--

00:59:20.855 --> 00:59:21.480
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:59:21.480 --> 00:59:23.040
AUDIENCE: Would you
recommend not doing that?

00:59:23.040 --> 00:59:24.748
ANDREW LO: Well, I
recommend not doing it

00:59:24.748 --> 00:59:26.760
from the financial
perspective, but I

00:59:26.760 --> 00:59:28.620
may recommend doing it
from the management,

00:59:28.620 --> 00:59:30.600
or managerial
incentives, perspective.

00:59:30.600 --> 00:59:34.370
The reason that companies
do that is very simple.

00:59:34.370 --> 00:59:35.964
They're trying to suck you in.

00:59:35.964 --> 00:59:38.130
They're trying to get you
to be more intimately tied

00:59:38.130 --> 00:59:41.670
to the company so you'll act
like an owner of the company,

00:59:41.670 --> 00:59:43.880
as opposed to an employee.

00:59:43.880 --> 00:59:45.950
And if you act
like an owner, you

00:59:45.950 --> 00:59:48.350
will engage in behavior
that is much more

00:59:48.350 --> 00:59:50.990
productive for building
the company's wealth,

00:59:50.990 --> 00:59:52.830
rather than as an employee.

00:59:52.830 --> 00:59:55.010
But from your
personal perspective,

00:59:55.010 --> 00:59:59.030
you're bearing risk
that you don't need to.

00:59:59.030 --> 01:00:01.810
So you know, the
analogy that I give--

01:00:01.810 --> 01:00:03.940
I've given before-- it
may work for some of you.

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:04.510
It may not.

01:00:04.510 --> 01:00:07.000
Let me explain.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:13.300
Anybody know how much window
washers in midtown Manhattan

01:00:13.300 --> 01:00:14.877
get paid on an annual basis?

01:00:14.877 --> 01:00:16.210
You know what I'm talking about?

01:00:16.210 --> 01:00:19.810
These are the folks that climb
up on these two-foot catwalks

01:00:19.810 --> 01:00:22.480
that are 40 stories high,
and they wash the windows

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:23.860
of these skyscrapers.

01:00:23.860 --> 01:00:26.079
That's a pretty risky job.

01:00:26.079 --> 01:00:27.620
Anybody know what
their annual salary

01:00:27.620 --> 01:00:28.760
is, when you annualize it?

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:31.496
I actually decided
to find out one day.

01:00:31.496 --> 01:00:33.620
I was kind of curious about
that because, you know,

01:00:33.620 --> 01:00:35.210
there's a trade-off
of risk and return.

01:00:35.210 --> 01:00:36.060
And that's really risky.

01:00:36.060 --> 01:00:38.476
You know, there was one day
when I was staying at a hotel.

01:00:38.476 --> 01:00:41.780
I think it was the Millennium,
and I was on the 30th floor,

01:00:41.780 --> 01:00:43.622
and it was a windy winter day.

01:00:43.622 --> 01:00:45.830
And, sure enough, there was
somebody there pulling up

01:00:45.830 --> 01:00:48.950
the thing, cleaning the window,
and looked happy as can be.

01:00:48.950 --> 01:00:50.420
You know, no problem.

01:00:50.420 --> 01:00:53.600
And I was thinking, boy, this
guy's taking a lot of risk,

01:00:53.600 --> 01:00:54.740
you know?

01:00:54.740 --> 01:00:59.070
And I hope he's
getting paid for it.

01:00:59.070 --> 01:01:01.700
And these salaries
are determined

01:01:01.700 --> 01:01:02.740
by supply and demand.

01:01:02.740 --> 01:01:03.420
What do you think it would be?

01:01:03.420 --> 01:01:04.410
Anybody have a guess?

01:01:04.410 --> 01:01:05.464
Yeah?

01:01:05.464 --> 01:01:06.730
AUDIENCE: About $70,000.

01:01:06.730 --> 01:01:09.860
ANDREW LO: $70,000, OK.

01:01:09.860 --> 01:01:10.500
Anybody else?

01:01:10.500 --> 01:01:11.176
Justin?

01:01:11.176 --> 01:01:12.170
AUDIENCE: $125,000.

01:01:12.170 --> 01:01:13.250
ANDREW LO: $125,000?

01:01:13.250 --> 01:01:14.709
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:14.709 --> 01:01:16.625
That's higher than some
NBA starting salaries.

01:01:16.625 --> 01:01:17.900
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:17.900 --> 01:01:18.710
OK.

01:01:18.710 --> 01:01:19.540
Leah?

01:01:19.540 --> 01:01:20.290
AUDIENCE: $30,000.

01:01:20.290 --> 01:01:21.081
ANDREW LO: $30,000.

01:01:21.081 --> 01:01:22.550
AUDIENCE: Do they take interns?

01:01:22.550 --> 01:01:23.620
ANDREW LO: Insurance?

01:01:23.620 --> 01:01:24.560
Interns.

01:01:24.560 --> 01:01:25.061
Interns.

01:01:25.061 --> 01:01:26.060
I don't know about that.

01:01:26.060 --> 01:01:26.620
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:26.620 --> 01:01:29.120
Well, so when I looked
last time, which

01:01:29.120 --> 01:01:31.610
is about four years
ago, it turns out

01:01:31.610 --> 01:01:35.300
that the typical window
washer for these skyscrapers

01:01:35.300 --> 01:01:39.430
gets paid about $60,000
a year, annual salary.

01:01:39.430 --> 01:01:42.040
$60,000.

01:01:42.040 --> 01:01:44.950
Now, you know, I
don't know whether you

01:01:44.950 --> 01:01:46.810
think that's a lot or a little.

01:01:46.810 --> 01:01:51.520
But, seems to me that
that compensation reflects

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:54.220
the kind of risk that
we're talking about.

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:56.860
And you know, you have no
educational requirements,

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:58.450
no degrees, no certifications.

01:01:58.450 --> 01:02:01.510
You just show up and,
you know, up you go.

01:02:01.510 --> 01:02:03.670
Now let me ask you a question.

01:02:03.670 --> 01:02:07.450
Suppose that a
window washer comes

01:02:07.450 --> 01:02:11.560
to the job who happens
to really enjoy dancing

01:02:11.560 --> 01:02:13.404
while he washes windows.

01:02:13.404 --> 01:02:15.070
In particular, he
dances that, you know,

01:02:15.070 --> 01:02:16.330
the Irish jig or whatever.

01:02:16.330 --> 01:02:17.710
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:17.710 --> 01:02:19.204
You know what I'm talking about?

01:02:19.204 --> 01:02:20.620
You know, that
dancing, the very--

01:02:20.620 --> 01:02:23.590
and he just likes to do that
while he's washing windows

01:02:23.590 --> 01:02:25.750
on the 40th floor.

01:02:25.750 --> 01:02:28.899
You agree that that's
more risky, right?

01:02:28.899 --> 01:02:30.940
Do you think that that
particular individual gets

01:02:30.940 --> 01:02:34.850
paid more than $60,000 a year?

01:02:34.850 --> 01:02:35.350
Why?

01:02:35.350 --> 01:02:37.821
He's taking more risk.

01:02:37.821 --> 01:02:38.320
Why not?

01:02:38.320 --> 01:02:39.611
Why isn't he getting paid more?

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:43.240
Exactly.

01:02:43.240 --> 01:02:44.830
He doesn't have
to take that risk.

01:02:44.830 --> 01:02:46.780
That's not part of the job.

01:02:46.780 --> 01:02:49.420
He can choose to take
that risk, but he's not

01:02:49.420 --> 01:02:52.840
going to get compensated for
it because it's not necessary.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:55.960
And there are 100,000 people
behind him waiting in line

01:02:55.960 --> 01:02:58.150
to get that job that
won't necessarily

01:02:58.150 --> 01:02:59.826
need to take that risk.

01:02:59.826 --> 01:03:00.522
Yeah?

01:03:00.522 --> 01:03:02.380
AUDIENCE: I thought
of it differently.

01:03:02.380 --> 01:03:04.006
If you had a long,
short portfolio,

01:03:04.006 --> 01:03:05.380
would it be the
other way around?

01:03:05.380 --> 01:03:07.380
Because you wouldn't care
about the market risk.

01:03:07.380 --> 01:03:08.590
You can hedge that out.

01:03:08.590 --> 01:03:10.442
You're thinking only
about specific risk.

01:03:10.442 --> 01:03:13.800
So like in that case, I would
short the guy who likes to jig.

01:03:13.800 --> 01:03:15.602
And I would invest in
the guy who didn't.

01:03:15.602 --> 01:03:17.560
ANDREW LO: Well, that
depends on whether or not

01:03:17.560 --> 01:03:19.510
doing the Irish
jig actually makes

01:03:19.510 --> 01:03:21.580
you wash windows
better or worse,

01:03:21.580 --> 01:03:24.190
in other words, where there's
an alpha to that risk.

01:03:24.190 --> 01:03:26.260
It may be the case that
dancing the Irish jig

01:03:26.260 --> 01:03:28.270
actually helps you
scrape off dirt

01:03:28.270 --> 01:03:29.470
that much more effectively.

01:03:29.470 --> 01:03:31.303
In which case, you may
not want to short him

01:03:31.303 --> 01:03:34.240
because then he will earn a
premium in certain markets.

01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:37.177
Those with lots of pigeon
poop on the windows.

01:03:37.177 --> 01:03:38.430
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:38.430 --> 01:03:41.020
So we can get into this analogy
more deeply than we should.

01:03:41.020 --> 01:03:42.190
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:42.190 --> 01:03:44.770
But the point is that, when
you think about the CAPM,

01:03:44.770 --> 01:03:48.560
all it's saying is that
you get what you pay for.

01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:50.150
And you pay for what you get.

01:03:50.150 --> 01:03:52.810
In other words, if there
is a certain amount of risk

01:03:52.810 --> 01:03:57.550
in a particular investment
that is risk that nobody

01:03:57.550 --> 01:03:59.560
can get rid of easily--

01:03:59.560 --> 01:04:01.780
in other words, you
have to bear it--

01:04:01.780 --> 01:04:03.430
then you have to pay for it.

01:04:03.430 --> 01:04:05.840
Because otherwise people
aren't going to do it.

01:04:05.840 --> 01:04:07.990
However, if there's risk
in a particular company

01:04:07.990 --> 01:04:12.280
that you don't have to pay for,
that you don't have to take,

01:04:12.280 --> 01:04:14.030
then you don't
have to pay for it.

01:04:14.030 --> 01:04:16.810
That's all that
the CAPM is saying.

01:04:16.810 --> 01:04:21.370
Beta is a measure of that
hard little pellet of risk

01:04:21.370 --> 01:04:23.080
that you can't get rid of.

01:04:23.080 --> 01:04:26.920
And the variance is the
measure of the entire risk

01:04:26.920 --> 01:04:29.570
in a particular portfolio.

01:04:29.570 --> 01:04:34.710
The only case where variance
and beta are the same

01:04:34.710 --> 01:04:38.050
is for what kind of portfolio?

01:04:38.050 --> 01:04:39.209
An efficient portfolio.

01:04:39.209 --> 01:04:40.500
What is an efficient portfolio?

01:04:40.500 --> 01:04:43.990
It's one that is already
maximally diversified.

01:04:43.990 --> 01:04:46.330
By adding more
securities, you are not

01:04:46.330 --> 01:04:49.960
going to do any better
than that straight line.

01:04:49.960 --> 01:04:55.090
All of these portfolios have
been completely diversified.

01:04:55.090 --> 01:04:56.000
How do I know that?

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.510
Because you're at the
tangency portfolio.

01:04:58.510 --> 01:05:00.700
There is nowhere to
go in the Northwest

01:05:00.700 --> 01:05:02.900
region off of that line.

01:05:02.900 --> 01:05:08.260
So for all of these securities,
the sigma and the beta

01:05:08.260 --> 01:05:10.450
are literally numerically
identical because there

01:05:10.450 --> 01:05:13.690
is no more extra risk
in the portfolio.

01:05:13.690 --> 01:05:15.540
It's been diversified away.

01:05:15.540 --> 01:05:19.190
But for Gillette, for Microsoft,
for IBM, General Motors,

01:05:19.190 --> 01:05:22.940
and Motorola, each of these
contain both beta risk

01:05:22.940 --> 01:05:25.580
and non-beta risk.

01:05:25.580 --> 01:05:27.500
The non-beta risk
is that Irish jig

01:05:27.500 --> 01:05:29.844
that you don't have to do
while you're washing windows.

01:05:29.844 --> 01:05:32.260
And you're not going to get
paid for it, I'm sorry to say.

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:36.170
So the relationship that
you want to focus on

01:05:36.170 --> 01:05:39.950
is the capital asset pricing
model's security market line.

01:05:39.950 --> 01:05:42.200
Measure the stuff that
you're going to get paid for.

01:05:42.200 --> 01:05:45.710
And this is what you're
going to get paid for it.

01:05:45.710 --> 01:05:47.335
Yeah, Ingrid?

01:05:47.335 --> 01:05:50.185
AUDIENCE: When you go back
into the sort of the real world

01:05:50.185 --> 01:05:54.000
and include transaction
costs, how do they enter here?

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:56.750
ANDREW LO: Well, so there
have been versions of the CAPM

01:05:56.750 --> 01:05:58.610
with transactions cost.

01:05:58.610 --> 01:06:02.150
And it turns out that it
doesn't change things too much.

01:06:02.150 --> 01:06:06.680
If you impose transactions
cost on all securities,

01:06:06.680 --> 01:06:08.760
and say that
there's a percentage

01:06:08.760 --> 01:06:11.790
cost for going in and
out, you can derive a net

01:06:11.790 --> 01:06:13.670
of fee transactions costs.

01:06:13.670 --> 01:06:16.040
It won't affect the
pricing necessarily.

01:06:16.040 --> 01:06:19.010
What it will affect is
the dynamics, the trading.

01:06:19.010 --> 01:06:21.620
What it will mean is that you
will rebalance your portfolios

01:06:21.620 --> 01:06:23.676
less frequently than
you otherwise might.

01:06:23.676 --> 01:06:25.550
But there is still going
to be a relationship

01:06:25.550 --> 01:06:28.190
between the net of
fee transactions

01:06:28.190 --> 01:06:29.940
costs of these securities.

01:06:29.940 --> 01:06:32.450
So you can actually look
at the transactions cost

01:06:32.450 --> 01:06:35.600
as a way to deduct the
expected rate of return

01:06:35.600 --> 01:06:38.444
from each of these securities.

01:06:38.444 --> 01:06:40.110
So transactions cost
is not a big issue,

01:06:40.110 --> 01:06:41.610
but there are other
issues that I'll

01:06:41.610 --> 01:06:43.662
come to that will be
a problem for this.

01:06:43.662 --> 01:06:47.064
AUDIENCE: Looking at this,
[INAUDIBLE] one of the best,

01:06:47.064 --> 01:06:50.466
efficient portfolio that I can
have is basically the index.

01:06:50.466 --> 01:06:53.870
If I want to allocate
my money globally,

01:06:53.870 --> 01:06:57.008
should I buy indexes
according to the market

01:06:57.008 --> 01:06:57.970
capital of the market?

01:06:57.970 --> 01:06:58.765
ANDREW LO: Yeah.

01:06:58.765 --> 01:07:03.026
AUDIENCE: This is the most
efficient portfolio I would--

01:07:03.026 --> 01:07:04.900
ANDREW LO: Right, so
that's a great question.

01:07:04.900 --> 01:07:07.530
And we actually have a separate
course on international finance

01:07:07.530 --> 01:07:09.238
that deals just with
those kind of issues

01:07:09.238 --> 01:07:10.410
because they're so tricky.

01:07:10.410 --> 01:07:12.270
But I'll give you
the short answer.

01:07:12.270 --> 01:07:16.590
According to the theory,
this tangency portfolio

01:07:16.590 --> 01:07:19.950
is not just for the
US stock market.

01:07:19.950 --> 01:07:23.560
It should be for the world
stock market, everything.

01:07:23.560 --> 01:07:25.740
So this tangency
portfolio should not

01:07:25.740 --> 01:07:28.020
be the S&amp;P 500 or
the Russell 2000,

01:07:28.020 --> 01:07:31.230
it should be the
MSCI, or EAFE, index

01:07:31.230 --> 01:07:35.460
that has all of the assets
in the world weighted

01:07:35.460 --> 01:07:38.490
relative to their market cap
in that particular currency

01:07:38.490 --> 01:07:41.200
of the investor that
you happen to be.

01:07:41.200 --> 01:07:43.830
So if you're a US investor,
it'll be in dollars.

01:07:43.830 --> 01:07:46.680
If you're a Brazilian
investor, it'll be in real.

01:07:46.680 --> 01:07:50.073
It'll be in whatever
currency you trade in.

01:07:50.073 --> 01:07:54.590
But that presupposes
that there's

01:07:54.590 --> 01:07:57.960
capital market integration
throughout the world.

01:07:57.960 --> 01:08:01.910
So in other words, if I call
this the world portfolio,

01:08:01.910 --> 01:08:04.700
implicitly I'm
assuming that you're

01:08:04.700 --> 01:08:09.440
free to trade stocks in any
part of the world freely.

01:08:09.440 --> 01:08:11.809
There are no
barriers to trading.

01:08:11.809 --> 01:08:13.350
And we know that
that's not the case.

01:08:13.350 --> 01:08:14.930
There are barriers, in fact.

01:08:14.930 --> 01:08:17.569
So what that means is
that the CAPM, applied

01:08:17.569 --> 01:08:21.020
to international stocks, is an
approximation that may actually

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:24.990
be worse than applying
it country by country

01:08:24.990 --> 01:08:28.220
and then looking to see
whether there are any distances

01:08:28.220 --> 01:08:31.556
or discrepancies across
those different countries.

01:08:31.556 --> 01:08:33.680
But people have come up
with international versions

01:08:33.680 --> 01:08:34.939
of the CAPM.

01:08:34.939 --> 01:08:36.410
And they don't work very well.

01:08:36.410 --> 01:08:39.300
At least, they didn't
as of 10 years ago.

01:08:39.300 --> 01:08:41.510
Within the last 10
years, a lot has changed.

01:08:41.510 --> 01:08:44.000
So it could be that
capital market integration

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:47.029
has made the world
CAPM look a lot better

01:08:47.029 --> 01:08:49.237
in terms of the data.

01:08:49.237 --> 01:08:50.649
OK.

01:08:50.649 --> 01:08:54.221
Other questions?

01:08:54.221 --> 01:08:54.720
All right.

01:08:54.720 --> 01:08:59.580
So now I'm going to talk
about implementing it.

01:08:59.580 --> 01:09:01.920
And we're going to deal
with all of the messy issues

01:09:01.920 --> 01:09:05.250
that I tried to put
off a lecture ago.

01:09:05.250 --> 01:09:07.340
How do you take this
thing out for a spin?

01:09:07.340 --> 01:09:10.189
Well, one thing you
could do is to try

01:09:10.189 --> 01:09:13.200
to test the CAPM
to see if it works.

01:09:13.200 --> 01:09:16.740
And one way to test it
is to ask the question,

01:09:16.740 --> 01:09:20.180
if we assume that all
securities are priced according

01:09:20.180 --> 01:09:25.479
to this equation, then another
way to write the equation that

01:09:25.479 --> 01:09:28.540
doesn't rely on expected
returns, but relies

01:09:28.540 --> 01:09:33.130
on realized returns, is to write
it as a regression equation,

01:09:33.130 --> 01:09:35.710
as you did in DMD.

01:09:35.710 --> 01:09:39.670
The regression equation is the
return, the actual realized

01:09:39.670 --> 01:09:45.640
return on security i, is
given by the risk-free rate

01:09:45.640 --> 01:09:49.510
plus beta times the realized
return on the market

01:09:49.510 --> 01:09:54.149
minus the risk-free
rate plus epsilon.

01:09:54.149 --> 01:10:01.380
Epsilon is the error term,
the disturbance, the residual,

01:10:01.380 --> 01:10:04.230
that is giving you
the fluctuations

01:10:04.230 --> 01:10:06.700
around the expected value.

01:10:06.700 --> 01:10:09.690
So when we remove the expected
values from this equation,

01:10:09.690 --> 01:10:12.120
we have to stick in
this epsilon term that

01:10:12.120 --> 01:10:13.290
sort of bounces around.

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:18.960
By the way, when you
look at this equation,

01:10:18.960 --> 01:10:21.690
you now have an
explicit representation

01:10:21.690 --> 01:10:27.990
for systematic risk
and idiosyncratic risk.

01:10:27.990 --> 01:10:30.960
For a given return,
it's comprised

01:10:30.960 --> 01:10:36.480
of three pieces, the risk-free
rate, beta times the market

01:10:36.480 --> 01:10:42.050
return that bounces around, and
this epsilon is the Irish jig.

01:10:42.050 --> 01:10:45.890
That is the idiosyncratic
bouncing around

01:10:45.890 --> 01:10:47.491
that you don't get
any reward for.

01:10:47.491 --> 01:10:49.490
How do you know you don't
get any reward for it?

01:10:49.490 --> 01:10:53.570
Because on average, the expected
value of this is equal to 0.

01:10:53.570 --> 01:10:54.680
How do I know that?

01:10:54.680 --> 01:10:58.550
By definition that's how I got
from this equation down here.

01:10:58.550 --> 01:11:01.250
If you take the expected
value of this equation,

01:11:01.250 --> 01:11:03.560
the only way that the
expected value of this

01:11:03.560 --> 01:11:05.480
gives you this
equation on the top

01:11:05.480 --> 01:11:08.240
is if that epsilon has a 0 mean.

01:11:08.240 --> 01:11:13.520
So you don't get paid
for bearing epsilon risk.

01:11:13.520 --> 01:11:15.480
It's there.

01:11:15.480 --> 01:11:18.582
And for some stocks it's huge.

01:11:18.582 --> 01:11:20.290
But you don't get paid
for it because you

01:11:20.290 --> 01:11:21.520
don't have to bear it.

01:11:21.520 --> 01:11:22.750
And the reason you
don't have to bear it

01:11:22.750 --> 01:11:24.220
is, if you take
50 of these stocks

01:11:24.220 --> 01:11:28.400
and stick them in a portfolio,
the epsilons average out to 0.

01:11:28.400 --> 01:11:29.730
How do I know that?

01:11:29.730 --> 01:11:32.650
Well, this relies on
a piece of mathematics

01:11:32.650 --> 01:11:34.470
that's known as the
law of large numbers.

01:11:34.470 --> 01:11:37.160
You may have heard that term
used in casual conversation,

01:11:37.160 --> 01:11:38.750
but it's actually
a real theorem.

01:11:38.750 --> 01:11:40.670
What it says is that
when you have large,

01:11:40.670 --> 01:11:43.730
large numbers of
fluctuations that are not

01:11:43.730 --> 01:11:45.890
correlated with each other--

01:11:45.890 --> 01:11:48.680
and by definition,
idiosyncratic risks

01:11:48.680 --> 01:11:51.349
for Gillette and Microsoft
and other companies

01:11:51.349 --> 01:11:53.390
are not correlated because
they're idiosyncratic.

01:11:53.390 --> 01:11:55.131
They're unique to those firms.

01:11:55.131 --> 01:11:57.380
That when you get a large
number of these uncorrelated

01:11:57.380 --> 01:12:01.970
fluctuations, that in the
limit, they actually go to 0.

01:12:01.970 --> 01:12:04.250
You can disregard them.

01:12:04.250 --> 01:12:06.140
So the law of large
numbers is what

01:12:06.140 --> 01:12:09.380
tells you that this
idiosyncratic risk is not

01:12:09.380 --> 01:12:12.380
going to be something
you will get paid for.

01:12:12.380 --> 01:12:18.050
So this is the CAPM
relationship using actual data.

01:12:18.050 --> 01:12:23.420
And if we stick in an alpha term
to represent deviations from

01:12:23.420 --> 01:12:26.480
the CAPM, and I subtract the
risk-free rate from both sides,

01:12:26.480 --> 01:12:29.030
just to have everything
in excess returns,

01:12:29.030 --> 01:12:35.960
then the CAPM reduces to the
hypothesis that the alpha--

01:12:35.960 --> 01:12:39.680
across all stocks, all
managers, all projects,

01:12:39.680 --> 01:12:42.190
the alpha is equal to 0.

01:12:42.190 --> 01:12:44.662
That's what the CAPM says.

01:12:44.662 --> 01:12:48.380
And if you want to
formulate it strictly

01:12:48.380 --> 01:12:51.410
in terms of total
rates of return,

01:12:51.410 --> 01:12:54.560
it says that the alpha has to
be equal to the risk-free rate

01:12:54.560 --> 01:12:55.800
times 1 minus beta.

01:12:55.800 --> 01:12:57.920
This is a different
alpha than this alpha.

01:12:57.920 --> 01:13:02.290
This alpha represents the
excess rate of return.

01:13:02.290 --> 01:13:05.290
OK, so let's do it.

01:13:05.290 --> 01:13:07.700
Let's see whether
or not it's true.

01:13:07.700 --> 01:13:10.600
Let's take a bunch of stocks,
subtract the risk-free rate

01:13:10.600 --> 01:13:15.510
from the stock returns, run
a regression of that stock's

01:13:15.510 --> 01:13:21.660
return on a constant and
the market excess return,

01:13:21.660 --> 01:13:24.940
and let's see whether the
intercept is equal to 0.

01:13:24.940 --> 01:13:32.760
Well, if you do this for two
stocks, Biogen and Motorola--

01:13:32.760 --> 01:13:40.940
I've done this from
1988 to I think 2006.

01:13:40.940 --> 01:13:44.210
When you run that regression,
here's what you get.

01:13:44.210 --> 01:13:54.130
For Biogen, the beta is
1.43, the intercept 1.61%,

01:13:54.130 --> 01:13:57.850
and the standard error is 1.1%.

01:13:57.850 --> 01:14:02.440
And then Rf times 1
minus beta is minus 2.1%.

01:14:02.440 --> 01:14:08.020
This should be equal to the
alpha in that previous equation

01:14:08.020 --> 01:14:10.180
that I gave you.

01:14:10.180 --> 01:14:15.280
So in other words, the alpha
that we've estimated for Biogen

01:14:15.280 --> 01:14:19.640
using this CAPM
regression is 3.7%,

01:14:19.640 --> 01:14:24.940
or on a monthly basis 45% alpha.

01:14:24.940 --> 01:14:29.620
Biogen is an incredibly good
buy according to the CAPM,

01:14:29.620 --> 01:14:31.330
if you believe the CAPM.

01:14:31.330 --> 01:14:32.700
All right.

01:14:32.700 --> 01:14:35.760
Now that's Biogen.
What about Motorola?

01:14:35.760 --> 01:14:38.040
During the same period,
when you estimate Motorola,

01:14:38.040 --> 01:14:40.500
it's got a beta of 1.42.

01:14:40.500 --> 01:14:45.630
And we're estimating an alpha
not quite as big, but 23.5%

01:14:45.630 --> 01:14:47.550
percent on an annualized basis.

01:14:47.550 --> 01:14:50.560
That's still pretty big.

01:14:50.560 --> 01:14:54.310
So if you run this
regression and analyze it,

01:14:54.310 --> 01:14:58.120
this is what you would
conclude, that these two stocks

01:14:58.120 --> 01:15:00.410
are wonderful buys.

01:15:00.410 --> 01:15:02.260
What we're going to
talk about next time

01:15:02.260 --> 01:15:04.990
is whether this interpretation
really makes sense,

01:15:04.990 --> 01:15:07.076
or whether we've got
some missing factors,

01:15:07.076 --> 01:15:08.950
or whether we're measuring
things improperly.

01:15:08.950 --> 01:15:10.700
We're going to need
to do a bit more work.

01:15:10.700 --> 01:15:13.180
But we're very close to
being able to figure out

01:15:13.180 --> 01:15:15.340
exactly how all of
these pricing models

01:15:15.340 --> 01:15:19.360
work in tandem with the kinds
of risk budgeting calculations

01:15:19.360 --> 01:15:22.100
that we're going to need to
do for the rest of the course.

01:15:22.100 --> 01:15:24.120
So I'll see you on Monday.

